$$
\begin{align*}
    \alpha &= \frac{\Delta L}{L_0 \Delta T} \\
    &= \frac{2 \, \text{cm}}{L_0 \cdot 50^\circ \text{C}} \, .
\end{align*}
$$

To find the expansion when heated by an additional $25^\circ$C, we can use the formula:

$$
\begin{align*}
    \Delta L_\text{additional} &= \alpha L_0 \Delta T_\text{additional} \\
    &= \alpha L_0 (25^\circ \text{C}) \, .
\end{align*}
$$

Now, we can calculate the expansion when heated by an additional $25^\circ$C:

$$
\begin{align*}
    \Delta L_\text{additional} &= \alpha L_0 (25^\circ \text{C}) \\
    &= \frac{2 \, \text{cm}}{L_0 \cdot 50^\circ \text{C}} \cdot L_0 \cdot 25^\circ \text{C} \\
    &= \frac{2 \, \text{cm} \cdot 25^\circ \text{C}}{50^\circ \text{C}} \\
